Customer Segmentation

25 August, 2022

The transaction data for channel partners(customer) of a large FMCG company is available. The data available is for two years -by month of the year and brand. The marketing team wants to create segments of customers based on transaction pattern so that marketing strategies can be developed for each segment.

 

Objective: To create segments of similar customers which can be used for marketing strategies

 

Packages/Libraries required

library(dplyr)
library(purrr)
library(flextable)
library(officer)
library(factoextra)
library(flexclust)
library(ggplot2)

 

Data Description

Following is a table of derived variables which are used in customer segmentation

Import the data “Transaction data for Segmentation” using read.csv function

setwd("D:\\Sankhya")

Derive variable sales_21

df1=df %>% group_by(CustomerID,Year) %>% summarise(sales_21 =sum(Sales)) %>%  filter(Year==2021) %>% select(-Year)

Derive variable sales_B121

df2= df %>% filter(Year==2021, Brand=="B1") %>% group_by(CustomerID) %>% summarise(sales_B121 =sum(Sales))

Derive variable BuyingFreq_21

df3= df %>% filter(Year==2021)  %>% group_by(CustomerID) %>% summarise(BuyingFreq_21 = n_distinct(Month))

Derive variable BuyingFreq_B121

df4=df %>% filter(Year==2021, Brand=="B1")  %>% group_by(CustomerID) %>% summarise( BuyingFreq_B121= n_distinct(Month))

Derive variable BrandEng_21

df5=df %>% filter(Year==2021)  %>% group_by(CustomerID) %>% summarise(BrandEng_21 = n_distinct(Brand))

Create masterdata by merging all defined variables

masterdata<- left_join(df1, df2, by='CustomerID') %>% left_join(., df3, by='CustomerID')  %>% left_join(., df4, by='CustomerID') %>% left_join(., df5, by='CustomerID')

Create plot for elbow method to decide optimum no of clusters

wss <- function(k) {
  kmeans(data, k, nstart = 10 ,iter.max = 1000)$tot.withinss
}

 k.values <- 1:15

  wss_values <- map_dbl(k.values, wss)

 plot(k.values, wss_values,
      type="b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE,
      xlab="Number of clusters K",
      ylab="Total within-clusters sum of squares")

 

Comment : Using elbow method, K=4 clusters are finalised

   

set.seed() is used to ensure reproducibility of the results given by kmeans function

set.seed(123)
k4<-kmeans(data,4)

Calculate mean of each variable clusterwise and round off values to two decimal places

allmean=aggregate( cbind(sales_21,sales_B121,BuyingFreq_21,BuyingFreq_B121
                  ,BrandEng_21,B121_Contribution)~segment_mean,data=masterdata
                   ,FUN=mean)
allmean=allmean %>% map(round,2) %>% as.data.frame()

Summarising each variables( average value) within each cluster

par( mar= c(1,15,15,1) )
for (i in 1:6) { 
  print((ggplot(allmean,aes(x=segment_mean,y=allmean[,i+1])))
        +geom_bar(stat = "identity",fill="blue")
        +labs(x="cluster",y=names(allmean)[i+1])
        ) 
}

 

Comment : Cluster one appears to be a cluster of “Platinum” customers whereas customers in cluster 2 is a group of under performers. Customers in cluster 4 are next to “Platinum” group but non-buyers of brand B1 relatively. Cluster 3 customers are mainly buying brand B1

   

Using K-median method of clustering as an alternative approach to K-means as the distributions of few variables are skewed

kmed4=kcca(data, k=4, family=kccaFamily("kmedians"))

Add cluster membership to the data

masterdata$segment_med<-clusters(kmed4) 
masterdata=data.frame(masterdata)
